06687nam a22007335i 9781978818309DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97819788183097 a10.36019/97819788183092doi  a(DE-B1597)641277  a(OCoLC)1345592193  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a384.55/320973223//eng/20220928eng00aPrestige Television :bCultural and Artistic Value in Twenty-First-Century America /ced. by Amanda Keeler, Seth Friedman. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2022] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (202 p.) :b35 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 The Fringes of Prestige TV: Genre and Markers of Distinction -- t1 Spies Like Us: Genre Mixing, Brand Building, and Reagan’s 1980s in The Americans -- t2 Disrupting the Pattern of Prestige TV: Fringe -- t3 “But Is It Star Trek?” Prestige, Fandom, and the Return of Star Trek to Television -- t4 Negotiating Prestige on The CW: Is Roswell, New Mexico “Another Show about Teenagers Getting F-cked Up and Having Sex” or a Sophisticated Exploration of Racial and Gender Politics? -- tPart 2 How Contemporary Programming Met Prestige TV: Unconventional Depictions of Cultural and Televisual Norms -- t5 Prestige Adaptation by Design: The Commercial Appeal of Latinx Tropes in Queen of the South -- t6 “Tell Them We Are Gone” Imperial Narratives, Indigenous Perspectives, and Prestige in The Terror -- t7 Prestige Comedy: Contemporary Sitcom Narrative and Complexity in How I Met Your Mother -- tPart 3 Top of the Media Hierarchy: Cinematization and Television’s Elevation -- t8 Running The Knick Show: Transfusing Steven Soderbergh’s Authorial Persona into the Prestige Medical Series -- t9 Legitimating Top of the Lake: Jane Campion, the Film Fest, and the Miniseries -- t10 Specters of Serling: Authorship, Television History, and Inherited Prestige in The Twilight Zone (2019–2020) -- tAcknowledgments -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrestige Television explores how a growing array of 21st century US programming is produced and received in ways that elevate select series above the competition in a saturated market. Contributing authors demonstrate that these shows are positioned and understood as comprising an increasingly recognizable genre characterized by familiar markers of distinction. In contrast to most accounts of elite categorizations of contemporary US television programming that center on HBO and its primary streaming rivals, these essays examine how efforts to imbue series with prestigious or elevated status now permeate the rest of the medium, including network as well as basic and undervalued premium cable channels. Case study chapters focusing on diverse series, ranging from widely recognized examples such as The Americans (2013-2018) and The Knick (2014-15) to contested examples like Queen of the South (2016-2021) and How I Met Your Mother (2005-2014), highlight how contributing authors extend conceptions of the genre beyond expected parameters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aTV history, television, TV shows, TV production, live production, newscasters, producers, producer strategies, directors, actors, TV programming, Smart TV, LG TV, TV remotes, marketing strategies, TV marketing and advertising, TV advertising, storytelling for TV, TV scriptwriting, screenwriting.1 aBarth, Josie Torres, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottomley, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c